						img.articlevertimg.center-block(src="http://res.cloudinary.com/jhi5/image/upload/e_auto_contrast,q_54:420,r_25/v1498676135/impersonate.jpg")
						h4.articleskilltext Impersonate is an Action card available in Silicon Artist's deck. Played by itself, you may choose to Stretch one of your Utilities and then gain 2 points of healing.

				p.articletext These two cards play well together! Let's walk through it. 

				p.articletext In order to Stretch, you'll need to have a Utility in play. Ballooning Bicep looks like a great card to have in multiples, so let's put it into play.

				img(src="http://res.cloudinary.com/jhi5/image/upload/v1500588106/saanim1.gif").center-block

				p.articletext Here comes the hard part. In order for Stretch to work, we need to pay close attention to which Utility slot is chosen when playing Ballooning Bicep. If we put it in the right-most Utility slot, we won't be able to shift it over and create the STRETCHED! card in its place. That's why it's always best to play Silicon Artist's Utilities in the left-most Utility slot as a default.

				p.articletext Now that Ballooning Bicep is in place, we can stretch it out by playing Impersonate. Let's make a copy. 

				p.articletext To stretch Ballooning Bicep, move it one slot to the right and put a STRETCHED! card in its place.
			
				p.articletext At the end of our turn, we have an interesting choice. Ballooning Bicep allows us to destroy it at the end of our turn in order to draw a card. That means we could also destroy our STRETCHED! card to draw a card as well! 

				p.articletext Let's look at another example of getting value out of our STRETCHED! cards.

